cycle, but not with every heart beat.

The rhythmicity of sympathetic nerve activity

87

ganglia, dierent neurotransmitters and neuromodulators can alter transmission of information (Glusman, 1989). Electrical stimulation of sympathetic preganglionic axons elicits a range of excitatory synaptic potentials including fast cholinergic nicotinic, slow cholinergic muscarinic and slow noncholinergic potentials (Karczmar et al., 1986). The predominant view that ganglia have a relay function is supported by recordings from preganglionic neurons which show similar discharge characteristics to postganglionic activity (Bahr et al., 1986; Janig and Szulczyk, 1980). Furthermore Ninomiya et al. (1993) have shown that sequential section of preganglionic inputs to the stellate ganglion whilst recording, cardiac SNA, leads to a stepwise reduction in the level of SNA but no change in the frequency of ®ring.
16. THE AMPLITUDE OF SYMPATHETIC DISCHARGES
While this review has focused on the rhythmical nature of sympathetic discharges it is impossible to do justice to this area without considering that discharges vary not only in their frequency but also in their amplitude. Green and Heron (1967) were the ®rst to comment on variation in the amplitude of discharges. Their observations raised the possibility that this aspect of SNA may be under separate control from that of the frequency of discharges. They observed activation of right atrial receptors led to a reduction in overall SNA by reducing the amplitude rather than the frequency of discharges. Ninomiya et al. (1993) have proposed that the amplitude of discharges re¯ects alterations in the number of activated nerves within each discharge. It could be argued that a change in the mean amplitude of discharges could re¯ect the activation of dierent populations of nerves during stimuli, however, the enormous variation in the amplitude of discharges even between neighbouring bursts (Fig. 17) suggests this is unlikely, under normal conditions at least. In anesthetized cats, baroreceptor activation by increasing blood pressure a small amount with noradrenaline, produced a decrease in the frequency of discharges, but little change in the amplitude of these discharges (Malpas and Ninomiya, 1992a). However, chemoreceptor stimuli produced a selective increase in the amplitude of discharges. This supports the hypothesis that these two components of SNA can be dierentially controlled in response to dierent stimuli (Malpas, 1995). The question arises then as to the location and mechanisms responsible for this control. The possibility that control over the number of recruited nerves is located in the spinal cord was raised above. It should be noted that in the conscious animal this dierential control over amplitude and frequency is less distinct, where a full range of baroreceptor activation and deactivation produces a sigmoidal shaped curve in both variables (Malpas et al., 1996). This is not surprising since overall SNA also shows maximum and minimum voltages to changes in blood pressure (Dorward et al., 1985), however, there was some separation of the two variables when animals were

also subjected to hypoxia. The blurring of dierential control over frequency and amplitude components in the conscious setting may be attributed to the more open nature of the experiments with all aerent re¯exes intact. With hindsight, it is apparent that these ®ndings on baroreceptor action in animals had been pre-empted by observations on man: SundloÈ f and Wallin (1978) showed that a 10 mmHg variation in diastolic pressure caused a twofold change in discharge amplitude but a ®vefold change in the frequency of human muscle sympathetic activity. At that time the implications of these ®ndings for the control of SNA were not pursued, however.
Although it has been well established that the timing of sympathetic discharges is quite closely regulated (Barman and Gebber, 1980; Fussey et al., 1973) there is little information on the regulation of the number of nerves recruited in each synchronized SNA discharge. Variation in the amplitude could exhibit ¯uctuations which may cluster at several dierent sizes. However, if one plots the amplitude of a single discharge against the amplitude of the preceding discharge no relationship between neighbouring discharges can be identi®ed, that is, a large discharge was just as likely to be followed by a smaller discharge as it was by a large discharge (Fig. 18). Furthermore, this variability between discharges does not seem to be aected by some stimuli. For example, hypoxia although increasing the mean number of nerves recruited, does not alter the coecient of variation between discharges (Malpas, 1996). The amplitude of discharges follows a unimodal distribution (Malpas and Ninomiya, 1992d). Further support for the proposal that the amplitude and frequency of discharges are dierentially controlled can be found in a plot of the amplitude of sympathetic discharges vs the proceeding interval between discharges (Fig. 19). Although the intervals between discharges conforms either to a burst every heart beat or every two to three heart beats, it made no dierence to the amplitude of a discharge whether it was preceded by a long period of no sym-
